election_record.label: New Hampshire 1823 U.S. House of Representatives, Ballot 2

overview.note: The Official Results list Arthur Livermore with 7710 votes, Edmund Parker with 6236 votes and Richard Odell with 5921 votes.

"Judge Livermore will receive a certificate of election under the provisions of the law relative to a second trial, although he has not received a majority of all the votes." Farmer's Cabinet (Amherst, NH). May 24, 1823.

"Mr. Hill has also a personal quarrel with Judge Livermore, the republican candidate for representative to congress at the election on Tuesday next - he therefore is using his utmost exertions to prevent his election, and to ensure the election of Edmund Parker, the federal candidate! The ground of this quarrel appears to be, that Isaac published something respecting Judge L. which was not true, and the Judge 'published him as a liar'!! - Is it then come to this, that the State must be embroiled to gratify the resentments of Isaac Hill? Must the harmony of the republican family be jeopardized to avenge his personal quarrels? Shall a federalist ride into office on the back of Isaac Hill's animosities against the republican candidate? Spirit of patriotism, forbid it! Forbid it, independent electors of New Hampshire!" New-Hampshire Gazette (Portsmouth, NH). March 10, 1823.

"We observed last week, that if Mr. Parker was chosen (a then probably occurrence,) he would owe his election to personal popularity. It is now evident that should he lose his election (a present probably occurence) it will be the result of a close coalition between the friends of the two Judges. - The federalists of the Eastern part of the State are entitled to all the honor of opposing Edmund Parker with all their might, to insure the votes of Judge Livermore's friends for the Rockingham Executive candidate." New-hampshire Sentinel (Keene, NH). March 22, 1823.

"The distinguished statesman, Judge Livermore, it is believed, is elected a representative to Congress; notwithstanding he was encountered by nearly the whole force of Federalism combined with all the choice spirits of the New-Hampshire Patriot. The greatest efforts were made by the editor of the Patriot to effect the election of Mr. Parker, a federalist of Boston stam But his design was not conceled or even disguised by the distribution of a few tickets for Mr. Odell with thirty thousand more containing the name of Mr. Parker with that of his noble general." New-Hampshire Statesman (Concord, NH). March 17, 1823.

"It is not almost certain that the Hon. ARTHUR LIVERMOR has been chosen to fill the vacancy in Congress which existed in this State, having received little more than one third of the whole number of votes cast at the late election. The county of Strafford, as will be seen by the returns, had it in her power to say whether Mr. Odell or Mr. Livermore should be elected: we regret to say that a preference was shown for the latter. It will be seen by a recurrence to the returns published in the last and present papers, that a major part of the federalists preferred the 'truly republican candidate,' Mr. Livermore, to Mr. Parker, who had always been a consistent federalist. In some towns nearly every federalist voted for Mr. Livermore, while almost every republican in the same towns (believing it necessary to vote for one of the two) voted for Mr. Parker!" New-Hampshire Patriot and State Gazette (Concord, NH). March 24, 1823.
